Then
\[5k \mathbf{v} = 2 \mathbf{b} - k \mathbf{a} = 2 \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} - k \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -2 - 3k \\ 2 - 4k \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}.\]Since $\|5k \mathbf{v}\| = 5 |k|,$
\[(-2 - 3k)^2 + (2 - 4k)^2 + (-2)^2 = 25k^2.\]This simplifies to $k = 3.$  Hence,
\[\mathbf{v} = \frac{2 \mathbf{b} - 3 \mathbf{a}}{15} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -11/15 \\ -2/3 \\ -2/15 \end{pmatrix}}.\]

We can expand the determinant as follows:
\begin{align*}
\begin{vmatrix} 1 & x & y \\ 1 & x + y & y \\ 1 & x & x + y \end{vmatrix} &= \begin{vmatrix} x + y & y \\ x & x + y \end{vmatrix} - x \begin{vmatrix} 1 & y \\ 1 & x + y \end{vmatrix} + y \begin{vmatrix} 1 & x + y \\ 1 & x \end{vmatrix} \\
&= ((x +  y)^2 - xy) - x((x + y) - y) + y(x - (x + y)) \\
&= \boxed{xy}.
\end{align*}

problem:
The midpoint of three edges of a cube are connected, as shown below.  Find $\angle XYZ,$ in degrees

[asy]
unitsize(1.2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, T, X, Y, Z;
pair x, y, z;

x = (2,-0.2);
y = (1.2,0.8);
z = (0,2);

X = (0,0);
Y = x;
T = y;
A = z;
Z = x + y;
B = x + z;
D = y + z;
C = x + y + z;

draw((C + D)/2--(B + C)/2--(B + Y)/2,red);
draw(X--Y--Z--C--D--A--cycle);
draw(B--A);
draw(B--C);
draw(B--Y);
draw(T--X,dashed);
draw(T--D,dashed);
draw(T--Z,dashed);

label("$X$", (C + D)/2, N);
label("$Y$", (B + C)/2, SE);
label("$Z$", (B + Y)/2, W);
[/asy]

solution:
We place the diagram in coordinate space, so that $X = (1,2,2),$ $Y = (2,1,2),$ and $Z = (2,0,1).$  Then $XY = YZ = \sqrt{2}$ and $YZ = \sqrt{6},$ and by the Law of Cosines,
\[\cos \angle XYZ = \frac{XY^2 + YZ^2 - XZ^2}{2 \cdot XY \cdot YZ} = \frac{2 + 2 - 6}{2 \cdot \sqrt{2} \cdot \sqrt{2}} = -\frac{1}{2}.\]Therefore, $\angle XYZ = \boxed{120^\circ}.$

Alternative, we can join midpoints of other edges, as shown below, to form a regular hexagon.  This makes it clear that $\angle XYZ = 120^\circ.$

